But frankly, not every game on the
App Store is incredible.

00:16:27.070 --> 00:16:33.060
There are a lot of games that are okay,
and they could be a lot better.

00:16:33.090 --> 00:16:36.870
And one of the things that a lot of
developers struggle with is creating

00:16:36.870 --> 00:16:40.660
something that is inviting that
leaves a great first impression.

00:16:40.700 --> 00:16:44.790
And the first impression for a game,
for an app, for anything really

00:16:44.790 --> 00:16:46.480
begins on the App Store.

00:16:46.500 --> 00:16:47.920
It's your icon.

00:16:47.970 --> 00:16:48.520
That's your calling.

00:16:48.520 --> 00:16:49.520
It's your calling card.

00:16:49.520 --> 00:16:53.160
It's the way you describe your game,
the App Store description.

00:16:53.160 --> 00:16:57.160
It's the screenshots that you select for
your game that people are going to view.

00:16:57.160 --> 00:16:59.420
Now, why is this important?

00:16:59.420 --> 00:17:02.180
Well, it's because people are
perusing the App Store.

00:17:02.180 --> 00:17:04.220
They're browsing the
App Store all the time,

00:17:04.220 --> 00:17:07.250
looking for the next cool game to play.

00:17:07.260 --> 00:17:08.070
Right?

00:17:08.100 --> 00:17:12.280
And they're going to pick your game out
based on what they see on the App Store.

00:17:12.280 --> 00:17:13.960
And so you need to have a great icon.

00:17:13.960 --> 00:17:16.320
You need to have appealing screenshots.

00:17:16.320 --> 00:17:18.250
And then your first impression,
once they see it,

00:17:18.250 --> 00:17:18.360
they're going to be like, "Oh,
that's cool.

00:17:18.360 --> 00:17:18.520
That's cool.

00:17:18.540 --> 00:17:22.450
I'm going to play this game."
And then once the game is downloaded,

00:17:22.450 --> 00:17:27.080
the first impression is reinforced
again and again as players

00:17:27.220 --> 00:17:31.980
relaunch the game over and over,
and your game starts up.

00:17:31.980 --> 00:17:36.110
And the question you really see,
the question to ask yourself and the

00:17:36.110 --> 00:17:39.870
thing to evaluate of your own game is,
every time it launches,

00:17:39.910 --> 00:17:41.680
does it launch quickly?

00:17:41.710 --> 00:17:44.680
Does it get people back
to where they were before?

00:17:44.700 --> 00:17:46.580
Are you saving the state?

00:17:46.580 --> 00:17:47.920
Are you building excitement
when the app is launched?

00:17:47.920 --> 00:17:52.240
Or do people constantly have to
wait for stuff to happen before

00:17:52.350 --> 00:17:54.760
they can get into the gameplay?

00:17:54.790 --> 00:17:56.790
No one wants to wait.

00:17:56.890 --> 00:17:59.520
Perhaps there's something
that's interfering with launch.

00:17:59.690 --> 00:18:04.510
So a great first impression is
really driven by being inviting,

00:18:04.770 --> 00:18:07.850
by launching quickly,
and constantly reinforcing

00:18:07.860 --> 00:18:10.700
that impression over and over
as people play your game.

00:18:10.750 --> 00:18:12.960
Now, great games are also intuitive.

00:18:13.010 --> 00:18:16.680
And this means that they should
show the player how to get started.

00:18:16.740 --> 00:18:20.270
This means that they should
provide feedback within the game

00:18:20.710 --> 00:18:23.140
that reinforces the gameplay.

00:18:23.210 --> 00:18:27.440
And games, just like apps,
should be intuitive and easy to use for

00:18:27.600 --> 00:18:30.020
the people that they were created for.

00:18:30.030 --> 00:18:33.010
I mean, there are so many
different kinds of games,

00:18:33.100 --> 00:18:38.640
RPG, casual, first person shooters,
all these different kinds of games.

00:18:38.640 --> 00:18:41.840
And different players are drawn
to different kinds of games.

00:18:41.860 --> 00:18:47.100
What one person understands
and likes with a logic,

00:18:47.100 --> 00:18:52.800
a casual logic puzzle solving game is
completely different from somebody who's

00:18:52.800 --> 00:18:57.600
playing a first person shooter like
Call of Duty or something like that.

00:18:57.600 --> 00:19:02.010
And so what is obvious in one
case might not be so obvious

00:19:02.130 --> 00:19:03.500
to a player in the other case.

00:19:03.550 --> 00:19:05.220
And so you really have
to define your market,

00:19:05.240 --> 00:19:08.090
understand who you're going for,
and then create a game that's

00:19:08.090 --> 00:19:11.030
intuitive and easy to use for them.

00:19:11.230 --> 00:19:14.580
And another attribute of great
games is that they're engaging.

00:19:14.690 --> 00:19:17.540
This means that they're addictive,
that they're sticky.

00:19:17.540 --> 00:19:21.860
Engaging games bring people
back again and again.

00:19:21.860 --> 00:19:26.940
You want people to download your
game and leave it on their device.

00:19:27.620 --> 00:19:30.630
In fact, what you're doing,
your number one competition

00:19:30.630 --> 00:19:33.710
is not so much other games in
your category or in your genre,

00:19:33.770 --> 00:19:36.050
but it's more for the
attention of customers,

00:19:36.070 --> 00:19:36.780
right?

00:19:36.780 --> 00:19:39.500
Just because someone has downloaded
your game doesn't mean they're

00:19:39.500 --> 00:19:40.980
going to play it again and again.

00:19:40.980 --> 00:19:44.240
And so your number one competition
is for their attention.

00:19:44.240 --> 00:19:47.290
And engaging games that leave
a great first impression,

00:19:47.290 --> 00:19:50.700
reinforce that over and over and over,
and that are intuitive,

00:19:50.790 --> 00:19:52.860
are games that don't get deleted.

00:19:52.860 --> 00:19:55.750
Your competition is really whether
or not customers are going to

00:19:55.870 --> 00:19:57.590
delete you off their device or not.

00:19:57.620 --> 00:20:00.170
And then your competition after
that is whether or not you can

00:20:00.170 --> 00:20:01.890
compete with other game developers.

00:20:01.900 --> 00:20:06.650
So engaging games are games that
players just can't put down.

00:20:06.650 --> 00:20:10.660
And they, you know,
they have to play just one more time,

00:20:10.660 --> 00:20:11.380
right?

00:20:11.380 --> 00:20:15.800
And I'm not a huge gamer myself,
but there are about 10 games that

00:20:15.800 --> 00:20:19.920
I love to play again and again that
I continue to keep on my phone,

00:20:19.920 --> 00:20:23.880
and they're the kinds of games
that I can't put down when I'm on a

00:20:23.880 --> 00:20:26.880
transcontinental flight or whatever.

00:20:26.880 --> 00:20:27.590
And I just, I can't.

00:20:27.620 --> 00:20:28.450
I keep wanting to play.

00:20:28.460 --> 00:20:29.490
I got to beat my high score.

00:20:29.500 --> 00:20:30.660
I got to beat my high score.

00:20:30.670 --> 00:20:33.300
And that's the kind of addictive,
kind of engaging,

00:20:33.300 --> 00:20:38.520
bring people back replayability
that's accomplished actually

00:20:38.520 --> 00:20:43.370
by having great gameplay,
frequent updates, fresh new content,

00:20:43.380 --> 00:20:45.520
and new game levels, for example.

00:20:45.550 --> 00:20:48.260
All of those things,
giving customers those

00:20:48.260 --> 00:20:50.720
things again and again,
over and over,

00:20:50.720 --> 00:20:55.450
bringing them back in with new levels,
new content, that kind of thing is what

00:20:55.570 --> 00:20:57.530
encourages replayability.

00:20:58.620 --> 00:21:00.640
And also, great games are social.

00:21:00.640 --> 00:21:05.040
And this means they create a real sense
of competition or reward or teamwork.

00:21:05.040 --> 00:21:08.610
And this is, you know,
they offer different challenges.

00:21:08.610 --> 00:21:12.360
And on iOS, this is largely accomplished
