So as the A6, for example,
on the iPhone 5.

00:27:17.280 --> 00:27:22.070
And what these extra registers
mean is that the LLVM compiler,

00:27:22.070 --> 00:27:26.130
for example,
that you use to develop your apps with,

00:27:26.150 --> 00:27:30.840
it can use these extra registers
to optimize assembly language

00:27:31.160 --> 00:27:33.610
and the Objective-C runtime.

00:27:33.620 --> 00:27:37.750
And so just by virtue of having
extra registers on the processor,

00:27:37.750 --> 00:27:40.830
we can optimize the
performance of iOS overall,

00:27:40.830 --> 00:27:45.840
and we can optimize your code simply
running it through the LLVM compiler.

00:27:46.840 --> 00:27:51.020
And because of all of that,
the A7 offers faster performance

00:27:51.020 --> 00:27:54.030
for both 64-bit and 32-bit apps.

00:27:54.040 --> 00:27:58.210
Now, if you're worried about the
switch to 64-bit and that

00:27:58.210 --> 00:28:01.240
it'll be difficult for you,
don't worry.

00:28:01.240 --> 00:28:04.310
You can easily maintain a
single code base and target

00:28:04.440 --> 00:28:07.040
both 32-bit and 64-bit devices.

00:28:07.140 --> 00:28:11.880
And we'll cover some techniques and
we'll cover details about how to do

00:28:11.880 --> 00:28:14.340
this in a session later on today.

00:28:16.400 --> 00:28:20.340
But what I want to make here is
that the 64-bit architecture of

00:28:20.340 --> 00:28:22.210
the A7 is here to stay on iOS.

00:28:22.530 --> 00:28:23.760
This is the future.

00:28:24.010 --> 00:28:27.030
And so don't put off moving to 64-bit.

00:28:27.410 --> 00:28:29.040
Now's the time to do it.

00:28:29.040 --> 00:28:31.350
This is where we're moving.

00:28:31.660 --> 00:28:35.950
The A7 improves CPU performance by
up to 2x when compared to the A6,

00:28:36.290 --> 00:28:39.620
but it also gives you double
the GPU performance as well.

00:28:39.620 --> 00:28:43.220
And you all know what the
benefits of a faster GPU are,

00:28:43.230 --> 00:28:43.940
right?

00:28:43.940 --> 00:28:49.460
There's more polygons, more sprites,
more particles, more complex shaders,

00:28:49.720 --> 00:28:52.900
more special effects,
increased frame rates,

00:28:52.900 --> 00:28:56.490
smoother animations,
more realistic lighting

00:28:56.540 --> 00:28:58.540
and visual effects,
right?

00:28:58.540 --> 00:29:00.980
These are all of the things
that a GPU provides to you.

00:29:01.890 --> 00:29:07.570
And ultimately it means that the
techniques that used to be too expensive

00:29:07.570 --> 00:29:13.440
for you to code or to employ in your
games are now totally within reach.

00:29:13.600 --> 00:29:15.850
I mean,
many developers would hold back because

00:29:15.850 --> 00:29:17.500
the hardware couldn't handle it.

00:29:18.990 --> 00:29:20.380
And now there's no reason to hold back.

00:29:20.480 --> 00:29:25.480
We believe that the new GPU,
the capabilities of a fast GPU like

00:29:25.480 --> 00:29:28.220
in the A7 are going to open
up a whole new class of games.

00:29:28.280 --> 00:29:32.810
And, you know, let's look at a leading
example of all of this.

00:29:32.950 --> 00:29:34.220
This is Infinity Blade III.

00:29:34.220 --> 00:29:35.300
You've probably seen this.

00:29:35.370 --> 00:29:36.120
You've probably played it.

00:29:36.180 --> 00:29:39.380
Maybe some of the authors
of this game are here today.

00:29:39.380 --> 00:29:44.400
We demoed this game on stage
at the launch of the iPhone 5S.

00:29:44.540 --> 00:29:48.620
And Infinity Blade II,
