00:31:43.620 --> 00:31:46.530
But there's more,
because the second trait of a

00:31:46.530 --> 00:31:49.990
next-generation game is that
it's always ready to play,

00:31:50.120 --> 00:31:51.140
to be played.

00:31:51.160 --> 00:31:54.730
And this is possible due to a
new feature in multitasking on

00:31:54.730 --> 00:31:58.540
iOS 7 that lets you do background
downloads of your game content.

00:31:58.540 --> 00:32:04.190
In iOS 7, we added some new multitasking
modes that all apps can use.

00:32:04.280 --> 00:32:07.590
And we did this in a way
that preserves battery life.

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:09.320
So let me be clear.

00:32:09.330 --> 00:32:13.660
Multitasking gives your app numerous
opportunities to stay up to date.

00:32:13.680 --> 00:32:16.640
iOS 7 does intelligent scheduling.

00:32:16.680 --> 00:32:20.110
So for example,
it notices when people play a game,

00:32:20.130 --> 00:32:22.000
when the game is typically played.

00:32:22.030 --> 00:32:26.550
And it gives background cycles ahead
of time so that your game can be ready

00:32:26.560 --> 00:32:29.400
to be played again at the same time.

00:32:29.400 --> 00:32:33.900
iOS 7 also takes advantage of the times
when a device is powered up to let

00:32:33.900 --> 00:32:36.620
your game do opportunistic updates.

00:32:36.630 --> 00:32:39.540
Maybe you want to go get some things for
your game for the next time it's played.

00:32:39.540 --> 00:32:41.810
And because the device powers up,
we give you some time

00:32:41.820 --> 00:32:43.560
to go get that content.

00:32:43.580 --> 00:32:46.040
And thirdly,
iOS 7 responds to push notifications

00:32:46.040 --> 00:32:49.330
as a trigger to give your game
time to fetch the information it

00:32:49.330 --> 00:32:52.860
needs so that when people tap on
the notification about your game,

00:32:52.890 --> 00:32:57.520
they're taken directly to the game
and it's ready for them to play.

00:32:57.550 --> 00:33:00.310
And this stuff wasn't
possible previously.

00:33:00.550 --> 00:33:07.090
Now, this is doable using three new
API tied to multitasking in iOS 7.

00:33:07.360 --> 00:33:10.600
The first is background fetch,
where we will launch your game

00:33:10.710 --> 00:33:15.560
periodically so that you can pull down
new data and update your UI accordingly.

00:33:15.620 --> 00:33:19.200
The second is remote notifications,
where we'll run your game in response

00:33:19.420 --> 00:33:24.280
to a silent push notification so that
you can update your content on demand.

00:33:24.330 --> 00:33:28.210
And instead of having to
poll your servers for updates

00:33:28.510 --> 00:33:30.260
when your game launches,
for example,

00:33:30.260 --> 00:33:32.460
which slows down that initial
launch time of your game,

00:33:32.460 --> 00:33:33.280
obviously.

00:33:33.290 --> 00:33:37.210
And it delays that instant
gratification for players.

00:33:37.530 --> 00:33:38.420
They launch the game.

00:33:38.420 --> 00:33:39.080
They want to play.

00:33:39.080 --> 00:33:41.720
They have to wait because you
have to go poll your server.

00:33:41.770 --> 00:33:43.860
That doesn't have to happen anymore.

00:33:43.860 --> 00:33:46.340
And the third part of this
is the background transfers.

00:33:46.540 --> 00:33:53.410
iOS can download content
updates in the background even

00:33:53.490 --> 00:33:55.400
if your game isn't running.

00:33:56.910 --> 00:34:02.130
Now, since you have new opportunities
for your game to be running on

00:34:02.140 --> 00:34:06.560
iOS 7 that didn't exist before,
it's even more important than ever

00:34:06.600 --> 00:34:10.760
that you are being power smart as well
when you do these background updates.

00:34:10.860 --> 00:34:13.140
So let me just touch on this briefly.

00:34:14.610 --> 00:34:20.060
Using the network, of course, obviously,
uses power because we have to power up

00:34:20.060 --> 00:34:23.980
the antennas regardless of whether you're
using cellular or Bluetooth or Wi-Fi.

00:34:23.980 --> 00:34:26.640
So when you connect to
an external resource,

00:34:26.640 --> 00:34:30.350
it's going to take power because
we have to bring up the antennas

00:34:30.350 --> 00:34:32.220
and the radios on the device.

00:34:32.320 --> 00:34:36.990
So do access these external resources
only when needed and avoid polling

00:34:36.990 --> 00:34:41.370
for information from your game
servers or wherever you're reaching

00:34:41.370 --> 00:34:43.480
out to for more information.

00:34:44.530 --> 00:34:47.400
Another thing here about
being power smart is that it's

00:34:47.500 --> 00:34:52.130
important to try to transmit the
smallest amount of data possible.

00:34:52.600 --> 00:35:23.900
[ Transcript missing ]

00:35:24.370 --> 00:35:29.680
So that's a brief touch on multitasking,
but on iOS 7, your game as a result can

00:35:29.680 --> 00:35:32.480
be always ready to play,
which is a great thing.

00:35:32.550 --> 00:35:35.520
I mean, nowadays, who wants to wait,
right?

00:35:37.390 --> 00:35:41.310
Next up is that
next-generation games are,

00:35:41.600 --> 00:35:43.930
iOS games are secure.

00:35:44.020 --> 00:35:47.860
And these days,
a lot of games are backed by a server.

00:35:48.090 --> 00:35:50.220
So it's more important
than ever to be secure.

00:35:50.220 --> 00:35:53.670
Most of the developers
that we talk with nowadays,

00:35:53.670 --> 00:35:58.000
certainly over the past year,
have some server infrastructure

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:00.270
that's supporting gameplay.

00:36:00.500 --> 00:36:38.600
[ Transcript missing ]

00:36:39.200 --> 00:36:41.690
And this is an important
thing for you to understand,

00:36:41.690 --> 00:36:44.770
particularly if you have
a server-backed game,

00:36:44.770 --> 00:36:48.040
because it has an effect on your
game if you use the new multitasking

00:36:48.040 --> 00:36:52.150
API to do stuff in the background
or when your game isn't running.

00:36:52.280 --> 00:36:56.430
So what happens is that data protection
will encrypt data on disk using

00:36:56.430 --> 00:36:59.000
keys based on the user's passcode.

00:36:59.080 --> 00:37:03.740
And when an iOS device locks,
we throw away these keys and may no

00:37:03.740 --> 00:37:06.230
longer be able to decrypt the data.

00:37:06.740 --> 00:37:09.330
So with the new
multitasking APIs in iOS 7,

00:37:09.470 --> 00:37:13.050
your game may be allowed to
run not only in the background,

00:37:13.050 --> 00:37:14.460
but also when the device is locked.

00:37:14.580 --> 00:37:16.290
These are new capabilities.

00:37:16.300 --> 00:37:20.260
But the problem is that potentially,
if you need to update your

00:37:20.260 --> 00:37:23.820
game in the background,
you're going to need to access

00:37:23.820 --> 00:37:29.450
credentials in order to obtain player
information from your game server.

00:37:29.460 --> 00:37:32.140
But if the device is locked,
you might not be able to

00:37:32.140 --> 00:37:33.610
get these credentials.

00:37:35.090 --> 00:37:38.920
So while data protection is important
for securing data on the device,

00:37:38.980 --> 00:37:43.830
it's equally important that you use
the latest best practices to securely

00:37:43.830 --> 00:37:46.710
transmit data over the network as well.

00:37:46.720 --> 00:37:50.860
And to do this,
it's important to use secure protocols

00:37:50.860 --> 00:37:55.000
and to verify certificates and,
whenever possible,

00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:57.300
to hash any sensitive data.

00:37:57.300 --> 00:38:01.140
And always respect your player's privacy.

00:38:01.140 --> 00:38:04.590
And we've got a session
that goes in detail.

00:38:05.190 --> 00:38:08.270
Around data protection and access,
credential access,

00:38:08.270 --> 00:38:11.580
and all of the things that
I just spoke of later on today.

00:38:11.580 --> 00:38:12.350
And you don't want to miss it.

00:38:14.290 --> 00:38:18.170
And just to drive home the point here,
making your app secure,

00:38:18.280 --> 00:38:24.440
making your game secure is not something
that should be an afterthought.

00:38:24.520 --> 00:38:28.250
It's important to plan for
these things in advance and to

00:38:28.270 --> 00:38:31.350
ensure a secure user experience.

00:38:32.010 --> 00:38:34.330
We have a session, as I said,
later today that will talk

00:38:34.420 --> 00:38:36.400
about this in more detail.

00:38:36.460 --> 00:38:40.230
Now, another attribute of
next-generation games is that

00:38:40.330 --> 00:38:43.000
they are designed for touch.

00:38:43.060 --> 00:38:48.200
And what this means is that when
you're creating an iOS game,

00:38:48.250 --> 00:38:53.270
it's critical that the controls and
interactions are designed with direct

00:38:53.400 --> 00:38:55.960
manipulation and touch in mind.

00:38:56.590 --> 00:39:01.340
Now, if your game was sort of, you know,
the genesis of your game was, you know,

00:39:01.340 --> 00:39:04.760
recently around iOS, then,
and you thought about

00:39:04.760 --> 00:39:06.860
multi-touch already,
that's sort of the only place

00:39:06.860 --> 00:39:10.430
that your game has existed,
then this is sort of a non-issue.

00:39:10.440 --> 00:39:12.420
Of course, it's going to be, you know,
touch-enabled.

00:39:12.680 --> 00:39:16.780
But if your game is coming to
iOS from a console platform,

00:39:16.870 --> 00:39:21.900
let's say, then the controller there
was designed for you already,

00:39:21.900 --> 00:39:27.320
but it had many built-in assumptions
about gameplay and interaction that

00:39:27.320 --> 00:39:30.550
may need to be reconsidered or changed.

00:39:32.680 --> 00:39:36.500
So it sort of depends on where you're
coming from with your game as to whether

00:39:36.500 --> 00:39:38.620
or not you are designed for touch or not.

00:39:38.800 --> 00:39:41.990
The best games on iOS create
controls that are designed for touch,

00:39:42.060 --> 00:39:42.780
as I just said.

00:39:43.050 --> 00:39:45.110
And this means taps, swipes, gestures.

00:39:45.110 --> 00:39:46.010
They work well.

00:39:46.010 --> 00:39:47.490
They respond immediately.

00:39:47.580 --> 00:39:49.610
They track beneath the user's finger.

00:39:49.610 --> 00:39:52.270
They give feedback, this kind of thing.

00:39:53.250 --> 00:39:56.800
And by touch, I mean, you know,
that touch defines the

00:39:56.800 --> 00:40:01.200
realm of possible controls,
and the controls define the gameplay.

00:40:01.420 --> 00:40:06.130
So it's the gestures and taps that
define the mechanic of the game.

00:40:06.580 --> 00:40:10.920
and the key is to create controls
designed around direct interaction,

00:40:10.920 --> 00:40:11.040
right?

00:40:11.140 --> 00:40:15.780
Direct manipulation reinforced
by instantaneous feedback.

00:40:15.800 --> 00:40:17.440
And think about that for a moment.

00:40:17.500 --> 00:40:21.860
Direct interaction reinforced
by immediate feedback.

00:40:21.920 --> 00:40:23.400
Does your game do that?

00:40:23.500 --> 00:40:29.240
So let's go back a few years and
look at a classic example of this.

00:40:29.280 --> 00:40:32.920
And I said to you that there are about
10 games that I play over and over.

00:40:32.960 --> 00:40:34.200
This is one of them.

00:40:34.230 --> 00:40:35.500
This is one of that 10.

00:40:35.530 --> 00:40:37.100
I love flight control.

00:40:37.150 --> 00:40:42.000
And this is flight control for FireBint,
if you didn't know.

00:40:42.090 --> 00:40:43.780
They're now part of EA.

00:40:43.820 --> 00:40:49.290
And this game instantly defined a
completely new genre of gaming when

00:40:49.420 --> 00:40:52.060
it arrived on the App Store in 2008,
by the way.

00:40:52.060 --> 00:40:54.360
This was a really innovative game.

00:40:54.430 --> 00:40:56.300
Talk about technological advances.

00:40:56.400 --> 00:40:59.740
These guys had dabbled with the
multi-touch capabilities of the

00:40:59.740 --> 00:41:04.500
SDK and had come up with the
game mechanic for flight control.

00:41:04.540 --> 00:41:10.680
And this is a game that was
designed for touch from the get-go.

00:41:10.760 --> 00:41:15.240
So what I mean by that is that you see an
airplane flying in-- you've undoubtedly

00:41:15.240 --> 00:41:20.380
played this game-- and you take your
finger and drag a path to the runway that

00:41:20.390 --> 00:41:23.490
corresponds to the color of the airplane,
right?

00:41:23.990 --> 00:41:25.580
And that's it.

00:41:25.620 --> 00:41:26.390
It's super easy.

00:41:26.390 --> 00:41:27.380
Right?

00:41:27.380 --> 00:41:28.190
It's really great.

00:41:28.230 --> 00:41:29.790
There's no other rules.

00:41:30.230 --> 00:41:31.280
That's how you play the game.

00:41:31.280 --> 00:41:32.920
And that's why it's so compelling.

00:41:32.920 --> 00:41:34.580
Because people just pick
it up and they're like,

00:41:34.580 --> 00:41:35.580
oh, is that all I need to do?

00:41:35.580 --> 00:41:36.470
That's incredible.

00:41:36.470 --> 00:41:40.220
And when this first hit the store,
this blew people's minds.

00:41:40.220 --> 00:41:42.790
But it's such a super easy interaction.

00:41:42.850 --> 00:41:45.150
But why is this so great?

00:41:45.230 --> 00:41:49.120
Well, it's because your eyes tell
you where the airplane is.

00:41:49.120 --> 00:41:53.380
You get audio and visual feedback
when you touch the plane.

00:41:53.900 --> 00:41:58.570
You feel friction as you draw
the flight path on the glass.

00:41:58.850 --> 00:42:02.120
And you see immediately
the path that you drew.

00:42:02.640 --> 00:42:05.750
And you see the effects of that action.

00:42:06.080 --> 00:42:08.240
Everything is in sync.

00:42:08.300 --> 00:42:14.930
And so, in other words, what you feel,
what you see, and what you hear all

00:42:14.930 --> 00:42:17.000
reinforce each other.

00:42:17.700 --> 00:42:20.440
This is what being
designed for touch means.

00:42:20.490 --> 00:42:25.000
And there are not enough games yet on
the App Store that do this correctly.

00:42:25.040 --> 00:42:29.130
And we want to work with you today to
make sure that your games are doing this.

00:42:29.310 --> 00:42:32.960
So what works best for when
you're designing for touch?

00:42:33.030 --> 00:42:35.580
Well,
what works best is game mechanics that

00:42:35.610 --> 00:42:37.840
are built around direct manipulation.

00:42:37.840 --> 00:42:41.780
Things like drawing,
dragging path gestures like we just saw,

00:42:42.060 --> 00:42:44.300
swipes, touches, and taps.

00:42:44.390 --> 00:42:49.140
And that's all versus game mechanics
built around indirect manipulation,

00:42:49.180 --> 00:42:52.500
like virtual D-pads
and virtual joysticks.

00:42:52.540 --> 00:42:56.830
Those are far less efficient,
and they're not designed for touch.

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:02.900
But there are games that are
based on indirect interaction.

00:43:02.950 --> 00:43:07.960
And those types of games are great
candidates for augmenting your touch

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:11.040
input with support for a game controller.

00:43:11.110 --> 00:43:16.700
And game controllers are super great
for providing the physical feedback

00:43:16.700 --> 00:43:22.380
that you need for indirect interactions,
